{
  "texts": [
    "A neural network, represented as f (x; θ), where x is the input and θ are the parameters (weights and biases), undergoes TL by adjusting a subset of θ for the new task while keeping some layers fixed, particularly the initial ones.",
    "There are two primary TL approaches: (1) feature extraction (Ma et al. 2019; Orenstein and Beijbom 2017), where the pre-trained model's fully connected layers are removed, and new, untrained fully connected layers are added for the target task (Marcelino 2018); and (2) fine-tuning (Vrbančič and Podgorelec 2020; Guo et al. 2019), where deeper convolutional layers of the pre-trained model are also adapted for the new task (Su et al. 2019).",
    "The mathematical formulation for fine-tuning can be represented as follows:",
    "(3) here, (x i, y i) are the input-output pairs for the new task, with θ representing the neural network parameters, divided into θ base for the base layers and θ new for the new layers.",
    "The goal is to minimize the loss function L. During fine-tuning, only subsets of θ base and θ new are adjusted."
  ]
}